                        <div class=3D"ttypography"><p>Not often wrong on ev=
erything. Tutorial on everything.</p><p>I understand that I came off as rud=
e but the reason I wrote that is that I'm frankly fed up with them. Because=
 every time I Google something, they are up there, taking up space, oversha=
dowing more deserving resources (note, I'm not saying my blog is necessaril=
y one of them). </p><p>I have worked as a developer, and you're right, it's=
 not just competitive programming. And it's also not just GeeksForGeeks. Of=
ten when I Google something, there are dozens of such sites that I have to =
sift through before I find anything useful. TutorialsPoint, C-Sharp Corner,=
 you name it. If it were just one site, it might be easy to say that you ca=
n just ignore it, but there are so many of them that I can't even keep up w=
ith them. And it's not that I have some kind of specific question that not =
every site should answer. I have <strong>never</strong> gotten any help fro=
m these. Worst of the worst is JavaScript, literally impossible to Google a=
bout without appending "developers.mozilla" (and/or domain name of your fav=
orite framework) to the search. </p><p>My resentment probably grew more dur=
ing my work as a developer, because I had to Google more.</p><p>And please =
don't say, "well, but you're not a beginner...". I have been a beginner too=
, it was not that long ago. Even if not in CP, I have had to take up some n=
ew programming languages which effectively means that I will be looking up =
initialization of a vector too.</p><p>Now about "often wrong". Well, I'm no=
t going to lie that I've conducted some sort of statistical survey of their=
 accuracy. It's just that there are enough stories about them presenting <s=
pan class=3D"MathJax_Preview" style=3D"color: inherit;"></span><span class=
