                        <div class=3D"ttypography"><p>You may be confused b=
ecause the word =E2=80=9Cflow=E2=80=9D can refer to slightly different thin=
gs.</p><p>Generally, a <em>network</em> is a graph with capacities assigned=
 to edges, and a <em>flow</em> in a network is a function that assigns a fl=
ow through each edge, subject to the <em>edge condition</em> (flow at each =
edge must be between 0 and the capacity of the edge) and the <em>vertex con=
dition</em> (for each vertex apart from the source and sink, the flow into =
the vertex must equal the flow out of the vertex).</p><p>When talking about=
 a <em>maximum flow algorithm</em>, the word flow refers not to a function,=
 but to a scalar value: the net flow from the source vertex to the sink ver=
tex.</p><p>So a flow in the first sense can have useless cycles that do not=
 contribute to the flow in the second sense. It's technically true that if =
you have a maximum flow (in the second sense) you can add arbitrary useless=
 cycles to it, subject to residual capacities, and it will still be a valid=
 maximum flow in the first sense. However, most maximum flow algorithms, in=
cluding Dinitz's algorithm which is explained here, do not generate useless=
 flows like that.</p></div>
